Kyle Korver hit a career-high nine 3-pointers
and scored 31 points Wednesday night to lead Creighton (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) to a
93-56 victory over Evansville.
article.headline: Korver hits career-high nine 3-pointers for Bluejays
article.linkText: Creighton's Korver dials long distance for 31 points
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Sometimes all a coach can do is just sit back and enjoy the show. That's what Creighton's Dana Altman did Wednesday night during Kyle Korver's shooting exhibition. The senior forward hit shots from as far as 25 feet in making a school-record nine 3-pointers in the Bluejays' (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) 93-56 victory over Evansville. Korver, who went 6-of-25 from 3-point range in six previous games against Evansville, was 6-of-8 in the first half on his way to a 31-point performance. Altman had no qualms with Korver firing away from long, long distance. "As long as they're going in, you keep your mouth shut and let him go," Altman said. "He was feeling it. Six-for-eight. It's kind of hard to argue with that." The Bluejays (14-1, 5-0 Missouri Valley Conference) equaled their third-best start in league play. The last time they opened MVC play with five straight wins was 1988-89. Creighton went on a 17-6 run in building 53-34 halftime lead, and the Purple Aces (5-8, 1-3) never got within 10 points the rest of the way. Larry House added 15 points and DeAnthony Bowden 10 for the Bluejays. Clint Cuffle led Evansville with 18 points and Ian Hanavan added 14. Korver, who leads the nation in 3-pointers with 70, bettered his career high of eight against Xavier on Dec. 31. Korver finished 9-of-14 on 3s, and the Bluejays were 13-of-26 from long range. The Purple Aces could never find an answer for Korver. Cuffle and Havavan took turns trying to guard him. "He's such a tough matchup," Evansville coach Steve Merfeld said. "He's got such a quick release. There aren't a lot of answers." Especially when shooting from so far away. "A couple of them were so deep, it probably shocked them," Altman said. Korver wasn't Evansville's only problem. The Aces also had trouble handling Creighton's full-court press, committing 12 turnovers in the first half and 23 for the game. Korver said he sensed it would be a special night after making two 3s from well beyond the arc in the first half. "They kept going in," he said, "so I kept shooting them." With each 3-pointer that went in, Korver's teammates just shook their heads. "When you're on the bench and you're watching it, you're like, 'Man, it's stupid,'" House said. "I mean, Kyle can shoot like I've never seen a person shoot before. If you leave him open, he's going to hit it."
